  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Dual Form (المثنى)",
      "titleArabic": "الْمُثَنَّى",
      "content": [
        "Arabic has a special form for exactly two of something, called the dual (المثنى). This is distinct from singular and plural.",
        "To form the dual, add انِ to masculine nouns and تَانِ to feminine nouns (replacing ة). The dual ending changes to ـَيْنِ in the genitive/accusative case."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Dual masculine: كِتَابٌ → كِتَابَانِ (two books)",
        "Dual feminine: طَالِبَةٌ → طَالِبَتَانِ (two female students)",
        "Demonstratives also have dual: هَذَانِ (these two, masc.), هَاتَانِ (these two, fem.)",
        "In genitive/accusative: كِتَابَيْنِ (two books)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كِتَابَانِ", "english": "two books" },
        { "arabic": "طَالِبَانِ", "english": "two (male) students" },
        { "arabic": "طَالِبَتَانِ", "english": "two (female) students" },
        { "arabic": "هَذَانِ كِتَابَانِ جَدِيدَانِ", "english": "These are two new books" }
      ]
    }
  ],
